    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-01-13T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-01-13T07:00:00-05:00" n="7"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d7">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13897: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-01-13T20:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 13, 1937—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:48 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>25. The broadcast from Sian last night in English was made not by woman announcer
                    but by a man who spoke English with a Russian accent. He announced inaugural
                    meeting of new “National Salvation Association” on January 11, with 200
                    delegates, at which time pleas were made for a “war against traitors” and a
                    united front against Japan. The work of various propaganda agencies was
                    described. It was announced that “peaceful conditions” prevailed in Shensi and
                    Chiang Kai-shek was charged with “insincerity”.</p>
                <p>Captain Barrett<note n="23" xml:id="d7fn23">David D. Barrett. U.S.A., Assistant.
                        Military Attaché in China.</note> reports today from Loyang that the
                    military authorities at Loyang believe that the present difficulty will be
                    settled without resort to military force.</p>
                <p>By mail to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
